description.text:
Update 29-1-2018

The canopy is a MOLD designed for vacuum forming. It is not designed to be printed and used as a canopy directly. This is how it is supposed to be used: https://youtu.be/6eHxSWjU11M

Low rider style camera mount and vacuum forming mold for E011, should also fit e010, F36, H36 etc. Camera mount designed for a split VM275T, any camera you can fit between ducts.

Print the camera mounts and heat them up with a lighter to bend it in shape. This allows it to be printed flat on the bed and you can choose any camera angle. Print a bunch of them because it takes a bit of practice to bend it perfectly and get it aligned. It's not perfect yet because the camera can rotate a little, but it does a good job holding it in crashes.

The canopy is designed to be a mold for vacuum forming.

E011 FC (Silverware firmware)

comments.text:
I'm sorry to hear about that man, but this is a mold designed for vacuum forming, as stated in the description. Maybe I should have emphasized that more. You can also press the Thingiview button on the model to view the model in 3D just like the render in the picture. Full 3D printed canopies are hard to print and either too weak or too heavy to work well. This is how it's supposed to be used: https://youtu.be/6eHxSWjU11M
I will add this video to the thing and an update to make it more clear.
However, all is not lost! Now that you have the mold, all you need to start vacuum forming are the following items:
-Shoebox
-Vacuum cleaner
-Plastic packaging material (or styrene sheets, or HDPE milk jugs, or plastic disposable dinner plates) I used the plastic the e011 comes in.
-A way to heat up the plastic (I used a heatgun)
-A frame to hold the plastic (you can make something out of wood pieces)
Here is a video explaining the technique:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixqTEu08vz8
This design is very easy to vacuum form because it's a very forgiving and easy shape. Once you get to learn vacuum forming, you can also make the traditional Tinywhoop canopy. :)

title: XY calibration sheet
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
My print bed area & XY calibration solution.

20 mm cubes didn't give enough precision for larger dimensions i.e. precisely spaced holes, so I made this "sheet" (it's only 4 layers thin, at 0.4 mm) in order to measure my printer steps/mm accurately.

The exterior dimension is exactly 180 mm. The holes and features have dimensions of 20, 40 and 5 mm (easy to figure out which is which), and are to be measured with precision calipers, in X, Y, and XY (diagonal). I've distributed the features along the sheet so I could check for any unevenness in sides.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

Quick tip: after measuring as well as you can, multiply the nominal (expected) value for the feature you're measuring (i.e. 180 mm, 20 mm, 40 mm etc) by the current steps/mm value in your firmware for the measurement axis, and divided by the value you measured. That's your new, more precise steps/mm value.

For best results, measure more than once, reprint and measure again.

title: K40 Laser Cut Air Assist (8mm O.D. hose with Needle)

description.text:
Remixed Avernois k40 air assist .Svg to work with my current setup. Very similar to his design, I just redesigned the armatures to accommodate my 8mm OD tubing and bike pump needle to get a better focus of the airflow on the material, and area being cut.

Be sure when assembling this, to start from the bottom and work your way up. Also the connector pieces (U shaped pieces) are intentionally by the original designers, slightly smaller than the surfaces they fit around. I found that using a pair of pliers to get even pressure when being put in place. This prevents damaging the material and breaking your process.

Also I attached the part to the gantry with a simple zip tie. Without using it, or something similar like an alligator clip, the part WILL fall off during operation. I found that a zip tie is a really sturdy connector, and also allows the part to be removed (not accidently) for maintenance or replacement.

Feel free to ask any questions or concerns in the comments!

description.text:
This is a case I created for the CPUville Z80 computer kit. For now I have the main board only, with the intent to interface it via my Arduino. Like an old-school homebrew computer kit, the Z80 Kit comes as a PCB, with parts to solder on. I figured the perils of my desk (paper clips, loose jumper wires, the occasional solder blob, etc.) were likely to short this thing out, so in the homebrew style, I took the opportunity to make a case for it!

This isn't my first 3D design, but it's my first 3D design with the explicit purpose of 3D printing. It's rough around the edges, correspondingly. But, it serves my purpose, and I believe it may be useful to others, so I'm posting it here.

  • This case design is Copyright ©2017 Ted McFadden (me). It's use is Creative Commons' licensed, CC BY-SA-NC. (Brief summary: Do what thou wilt, but if that includes an exchange of money with something other than a print service, please contact me.)

I really liked the Hyperlow frame by Kabab FPV (https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC4yjtLpqFmlVncUFExoVjiQ), so I thought that I would try and design a similar, printable design. This is designed to work with the Flite Test Gremlin Power Pack, which consists of individual 6 amp ESCs, the EMAX F3 Femto FC, and 1104 5250kv motors. The camera mount works with a skinny AIO camera like the Wolfwhoop WT05. I am upgrading to EMAX 1106 6000kv motors, so the motor mounts are compatible with both the 1104 and 1106 motor.

The battery mounts on the top of the frame, which is why the arms are so darn long.

Also, the arm tabs are intentionally too large to fit without sanding. With sanding, you can get a much tighter fit and no play in the arms.

You will need two M3 standoffs and four standoff screws to hold the frame together. Actually, when I printed this version of the frame out, the holes for the standoffs didn’t line up, but the standoffs were still able to screw in.

Files:
-1106vertarmthick.stl: arm with 4mm mount thickness; only compatible with motors that have screws that work for 4mm arms; stronger because more material

-chunky thin mount.stl: arm with 2mm mount thickness; compatible with 1106 motors or 1104 motors

-with retainers.stl: bottom plate

-short arms top plate.stl: top plate

NOTE: The arms on this frame are not terribly durable, at least in the PLA that I am limited to. I only have the ability to print in PLA, so I have actually moved to a carbon fiber frame for my Gremlin/2.5" components, so I will not be improving these files more. If you want a durable printed frame for PLA, not to sound stuck up or anything, but I would recommend the beefiest bottom plate in my Flite Test Gremlin Frame System, because I was not able to break it. The file names for the beefiest bottom plates are GremlinFrame2V2sidefillets.STL and GremlinFrame2V3_2mm_tabs.stl.

title: Snowblower for 1/10 Scale Oshkosh 4x4 RC Body

description.text:
So after months and months of designing and printing and wasting PLA, I have finally made a semi-working snow blower for my Oshkosh SCX10 body. I say semi working because I have only operated it once and broke after 30 seconds. I have, since the failure, redesigned and reprinted the failed parts. However I have not yet tested due to a few engineering limitations of my imagination. One issue that I am having is making a belt for the pulleys in the back. I started testing with extra 3d printer timing belt. So far its working, but haven't given it any stress or duration of run time. So any pointers would only benefit anyone who wants to print this. So I will be uploading STL files once I get a few more things figured out and once a final live test has been done. Their calling for some dry snow over the next few days so expect the STLs to show up soon.

Update 2/19/2018
All File to make this are uploaded
I'm unsure how much support I will be able to give but I'll do my best. The main front auger uses a STRAIGHT 1/4" steel brake line that slide into the two halves. You will also need 3 fidget spinner bearings. Two for either side of the auger (brake line) and one goes into rear to hold the spur pulley. Basically its powered by a 550 rc motor that turns a belt connected to the secondary drive pulley. I used a stepper motor pinion pulley with a printed adapter to fit onto the 550 motor shaft. The secondary drive uses a (16/1) worm gear to turn the primary auger. The belt is just a 3d printer timing belt. Making a belt out of the a straight piece of timing belt was the main holdup of the whole build. This is how i did it. Measured around the pulleys, cut diagonally so the ribs match up. Then I superglued it together. Got a very tiny drillbit to drill holes in the the ribs. Then used screws from a 9g servo to go into the ribs. I only used about 4-5 ribs. and then superglue again and...boom, you have a belt. The mounts are designed for the unimog and would use a body mounted winch servo to pull the blower up and down, however, it is really heavy so I had to hard mount it to the body and drive really slow. Now for a few suggestions, after most is assembled, glue the primary pulley to the secondary shaft before screwing it together. There only a 4mm hex turning the primary shaft. Mine striped out after a little. And I wouldnt used a brushless motor to power it all. I use a 55t crawler motor and that seems to spin fast enough to throw snow. Well, enjoy printing and I will do my best to answer questions. Oh...the whole thing is put together with M3 screws.

title: Precision Piezo Z-Sense Mount for Prusa/Anet v2

description.text:
This is V2 of The Universal Piezo Z-Sensing Extruder Mount

The original wasn't getting reliable flex out of the disk when mounted on a printer and used under normal conditions. This redesign hopefully will address that issue.

For reference, here's a video of the original mount on the test rig

And here's the recessed mount in action

and here's a gif of the mount in 3D

This Thing is a replacement X-Carriage extruder mount that incorporates the Precision Piezo sensor. It allows the printer to get pinpoint accurate Z-Axis offsets without any compromise.

Included in this thing are mounts for the original Precision Piezo, and two different mounting styles for my own PCB design that comes with several print head enhancements, which include:

  • Flat Flexible cable for transporting all signal and voltage for the cleanest possible cable chain.
  • Onboard voltage regulators allowing use of either 5v or 12v DC fans regardless of Vcc (PWM control still works)
  • LED's on all controlled traces for visual feedback

So what's it do?
this is a replacement for all z-probes, endstops, and other methods for detecting z-min. In simple terms, we're sandwiching a ceramic disk in between the extruder mount, that, when the nozzle touches the bed, sends a z-trig signal.

How does it work?
When a Piezoelectric disk is compressed, or flexed, it sends out a ripple of voltage. When the nozzle touches the bed, the entire extruder is imperceptibly pushed upward, causing torsion on the X-Carriage. Since we mount the Piezo disk in between the extruder and the X-Carriage, the disk flexes into the small cavity left behind it when the nozzle touches the bed. This in turn causes a voltage ripple, which is sent through an array of voltage comparators in the Precision Piezo circuit, which in turn then send the z-trigger signal wen the voltage ripple hits a certain threshold.

How is this better than z-probes like inductive sensors, or the BLTouch?
All of these methods, endstops, and z-probes, operate under referential circumstances. They are unfortunately prone to issues when things like the mounts are not secure, or your extruder's nozzle is changed, or any number of other factors. The Piezo Z-Sensor, on the other hand, has several advantages that eliminate most of the headaches of these other methods:

  • Uses the nozzle itself to sense, therefore there's no X/Y offsets
  • If swapping nozzles, or using a modular print head, the z-sensor is uneffected, as it works from within the mount. No need to re-adjust z-offsets
  • Extremely high accuracy and repeatability. the original developer claims 0.01mm accuracy
  • No deadzones when probing the bed - probe anywhere you can print
  • Works on ANY print surface

Where can I get one of these sensors!?
The original developer has an online shop where several different versions can be purchased. My own version is currently in validation testing, but if there's enough interest I could put a large batch together. Currently I'm doing them by hand so if you'd like one, just shoot me a message and we'll work something out.

A big thank you to all the people who helped develop the Piezo Z-Sensor in the first place, Nial Brekke, Mike Simpson, Idris Nowell, and DjDemonD for bringing this project over to Thingiverse!

Holds 550 paracord. There are a bunch of these out there, but I found the other designs lacking.

This holds 100 ft of cord.
This uses normal rectangular razor blades (aka scraper blades, Stanley 11-515).

This has notches along the sides for melting the tag end into a nice shape.
Blade guard is not flimsy.

Blade cover snaps in place and doesn't need screws. Feel free to glue it shut if you wish.

Usage:
Slip cord through top middle, tie overhand knot, pull into slight recess on bottom. Wrap tight.

Using melting slots: Find the slot that best matches the size cordage you are using. Leave approximately 1/2" above slot. Melt cord with a lighter. Pull cord down into slot (but not through the bottom). Wait for the cord to cool and remove. The end should have a nice round shape to it.

title: Santa's Sleigh (3 Piece Print - Body Remix)

description.text: I wanted to make one of these Santa Sleigh's for my wife (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2569627) but didn't want to use supports for the body. So I used the "Cut" feature of Slic3r to separate the sides from the body, then used scaling in Cura to thin down the sides to 3mm thick (from 5mm) and also widen the body middle 4mm (to 64mm) to make up for the thinner sides. The sleds are 5mm thick so this gives a 2mm inset on the inside to superglue the middle to the sides and sleds and hide the seam. Or you can "center" the 3mm body sides within the 5mm sleds to give a 1mm inset on the outside and still have 1mm inset on the inside to pop the middle into for a nice look also. I made a Left and Right of the sides (which you could just use mirror in your slicer too), so that we could decide whether to put the shiny sides (glass bed), or the top layer to the outside and have them match. Thanks ChrisF3D for the original design!

2 pat curtain holder. Specially designed for the moulding in my house. The gradual curve on the block is for the moulding. Made in 2 parts so it can be printed without scaffolding.

Yet another printable model of Steve from the Minecraft game. This model has loose but strong joints, and has already withstood a few weeks of play with my grandson.

In truth, one main point of this exercise was to explore the design of a single print with movable parts. There is no assembly required. Pop the print off the bed, remove the support structure, and you should have a working toy. (Suggest you print face-up. Painting the face and/or body is up to you.)

Have fun. :)

Really liked this design that I had seen on instructables* and wanted to create one that we could print. It takes a little bit of work but worth the effort! Reworked the drawings to better suite 3D printing and created a top cover to hold all the components together. Size: 4" Diameter
Each Component Thickness: 0.075"
  • Print all components and then drill the holes (to your liking) to make sure they are a perfect circle.
  • I am fortunate enough to have a lathe which I created my pins out of aluminum but of course you can use anything you would like to fit perfectly. I put a little bit of glue to hold the pins in place but be careful the glue does not run down the pins to seize the components.
  • Make sure that all surfaces are smooth so the components travel easy.
  • You may have to sand down the flaps to properly close the iris completely.
    • Enjoy! *http://www.instructables.com/id/Mechanical-iris-v20/ by NTT
